## Problem 1: Manual Scaling

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

Your e-commerce app runs on a single `t3.medium` EC2 instance. You launch a flash sale — 50,000 users flood in within 10 minutes. CPU hits 100%. Response times go from 200ms → 30 seconds → timeouts. Users can't checkout. You lose ₹40 lakhs in revenue.

You scramble to spin up more EC2s manually. By the time new instances are ready (AMI creation, launch, health checks — ~15 minutes), the sale peak is over.

To avoid this, you will create Application load balancer with Autoscaling groups and put the EC2 instance behind this setup. It will work but below problems occurs when you new application scales and user traffic grows continously.

### 🟡 EC2 "Fix" Attempt: Auto Scaling Groups (ASG)

AWS ASGs can scale, but:
- Scaling out takes **5–15 minutes** (boot time + AMI baking)
- You scale the **entire OS**, not just your app
- Cold starts mean new instances serve no traffic during warmup
- Scaling **in** can kill active connections

```
EC2 ASG Scale-Out Timeline:
[Traffic spike] → [CloudWatch alarm: 5 min] → [Launch instance: 3 min]
→ [OS boot: 2 min] → [App start: 2 min] → [Health check: 3 min]
= ~15 minutes of degraded service
```

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Kubernetes runs your app as **containers** (already running OS). Scaling is near-instant because it's just starting a new container process. all your application docker images already created.

<div class="mermaid">
graph LR
    A[Traffic Spike Detected] --> B[HPA reads CPU metrics]
    B --> C{CPU > 70%?}
    C -->|Yes| D[Scale pods: 2 → 10]
    D --> E[New pod starts in ~5 seconds]
    E --> F[kube-proxy updates routing]
    F --> G[Traffic distributed instantly]
    C -->|No| H[No action]
</div>



> ✅ **Result:** Scale from 2 → 50 pods in **~5 seconds**, not 15 minutes.

