## 4. Problem 3: Deployment Downtime

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

You have one EC2 instance. To deploy a new version:
1. Stop the app
2. Pull new code
3. Install dependencies
4. Start app

During steps 1–4, **your app is completely down**. Users see 502 errors. Even with a load balancer, if you have 2 instances and update both — you have a gap.

### 🟡 EC2 "Fix" Attempt: Blue-Green Deployment

You maintain **two full EC2 environments** (blue & green). Switch the load balancer between them. But now you're paying **double** the infrastructure cost 24/7, and coordination is complex.

```
Blue-Green on EC2:
[Blue: live] [Green: idle but fully provisioned]
Cost: 2x EC2 instances running always
Switch time: ~1-2 minutes (DNS/LB propagation)
Rollback: Manual LB switch (~2 min)
```

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Kubernetes does **rolling updates** natively — replacing old pods one at a time while keeping the others running. Zero downtime, no extra cost.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph "Before Deployment (v1)"
        P1[Pod v1 🟢] 
        P2[Pod v1 🟢]
        P3[Pod v1 🟢]
    end

    subgraph "During Rolling Update"
        P4[Pod v2 🔵 starting]
        P5[Pod v1 🟢 serving]
        P6[Pod v1 🟢 serving]
        P7[Pod v1 🔴 terminating]
    end

    subgraph "After Deployment (v2)"
        P8[Pod v2 🔵]
        P9[Pod v2 🔵]
        P10[Pod v2 🔵]
    end

    P1 --> P4
    P2 --> P5
    P3 --> P6
    P4 --> P8
    P5 --> P9
    P6 --> P10
```

```yaml
spec:
  strategy:
    type: RollingUpdate
    rollingUpdate:
      maxSurge: 1        # Create 1 new pod before killing old
      maxUnavailable: 0  # Never go below desired replicas
```

**Instant rollback:**
```bash
# If v2 breaks production, rollback in 2 seconds:
kubectl rollout undo deployment/ecommerce-api

# Check history:
kubectl rollout history deployment/ecommerce-api
```

> ✅ **Result:** Zero-downtime deploys. Rollback in 2 seconds. No extra infrastructure cost.

