## 5. Problem 4: Resource Wastage

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

Your app has 8 microservices. You assign one EC2 instance per service to avoid "noisy neighbor" problems. Each `t3.large` (2 vCPU, 8GB RAM) costs ~$60/month.

But your `notification-service` only uses **0.05 vCPU and 128MB RAM** during normal hours. You're paying for 8 GB RAM and using 128 MB. **That's 98.4% waste.**

```
8 services × $60/month = $480/month
Actual compute used ≈ 15% of provisioned
Real cost of waste = ~$408/month = ₹3.4 lakhs/year wasted
```

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Kubernetes **bin-packs** multiple containers onto the same node using resource `requests` and `limits`. You declare what you need; K8s fits the puzzle pieces together.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph "EC2 Approach — 8 Instances"
        E1["t3.large\n notification-service\n Used: 128MB / 8GB RAM\n 💸 Wasteful"]
        E2["t3.large\n auth-service\n Used: 512MB / 8GB RAM\n 💸 Wasteful"]
        E3["t3.large\n payment-service\n Used: 1GB / 8GB RAM\n 💸 Wasteful"]
    end

    subgraph "Kubernetes — 2 Nodes"
        N1["Node 1 — t3.large\n 🔵 notification: 128MB\n 🟢 auth: 512MB\n 🟡 user-service: 256MB\n 🔴 cache-worker: 512MB\n Total: 1.4GB / 8GB"]
        N2["Node 2 — t3.large\n 🔵 payment: 1GB\n 🟢 order: 768MB\n 🟡 inventory: 512MB\n 🔴 search: 512MB\n Total: 2.8GB / 8GB"]
    end
```

```yaml
resources:
  requests:
    memory: "128Mi"   # Minimum guaranteed
    cpu: "50m"        # 0.05 vCPU guaranteed
  limits:
    memory: "256Mi"   # Maximum allowed
    cpu: "200m"       # Burst up to 0.2 vCPU
```

> ✅ **Result:** Run 8 services on 2 nodes instead of 8. **Save ~$360/month per environment.**

