## 6. Problem 5: No Service Discovery

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

Your `order-service` needs to call `payment-service`. On EC2, you hardcode the IP:

```javascript
// order-service/config.js
const PAYMENT_SERVICE_URL = "http://10.0.1.45:3001";
```

Then the payment EC2 gets replaced (new deployment, spot instance reclaim, AZ failover). Its IP changes to `10.0.1.89`. Every service that called it is now **broken**. You scramble to update configs, redeploy everything.

### 🟡 EC2 "Fix" Attempt

You put an ALB in front of every microservice. Now you pay for 8 ALBs ($20/month each = $160/month extra) and manage 8 DNS records. Still brittle.

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Kubernetes has a built-in **DNS-based service discovery**. Every Service gets a stable DNS name. IPs change — the name never does.

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph "Kubernetes Cluster"
        OS[order-service pod]
        SVC[payment-service\nService\nClusterIP: 10.96.45.1\nDNS: payment-service.default.svc.cluster.local]
        PP1[payment pod 1\n10.0.1.45]
        PP2[payment pod 2\n10.0.1.89]
        PP3[payment pod 3\n10.0.2.12]
    end

    OS -->|"http://payment-service:3001"| SVC
    SVC -->|load balanced| PP1
    SVC -->|load balanced| PP2
    SVC -->|load balanced| PP3
```

```javascript
// order-service — works forever, IP changes don't matter
const PAYMENT_SERVICE_URL = "http://payment-service:3001";
```

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: payment-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: payment        # Finds pods with this label
  ports:
  - port: 3001
    targetPort: 3001
```

> ✅ **Result:** Services talk by **name**, not IP. Zero config updates on pod restarts or scaling.

