## 7. Problem 6: Secrets & Config Management

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

You have 5 environments (dev, staging, prod-us, prod-eu, prod-ap). Each EC2 has `.env` files with database passwords, API keys, JWT secrets. The problems:

- Developer accidentally commits `.env` to GitHub → **credentials exposed**
- You need to rotate the DB password → update `.env` on **every EC2 manually**
- New hire gets wrong `.env` file → **production DB wiped in staging**
- Secrets exist in plain text on disk — any shell access = full compromise

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Kubernetes has native **Secrets** and **ConfigMaps**, with proper RBAC access controls. Secrets are base64-encoded and can be encrypted at rest (etcd encryption). Integrate with AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault for enterprise needs.

```mermaid
graph TD
    Dev[Developer] -->|kubectl apply| CM[ConfigMap\nnon-sensitive config]
    Ops[DevOps/SRE] -->|kubectl create secret| SEC[Secret\nencrypted in etcd]
    Vault[AWS Secrets Manager\nor Vault] -->|External Secrets Operator| SEC

    SEC -->|mounted as env vars\nor files| Pod1[payment-service pod]
    CM -->|mounted as env vars| Pod1
    CM -->|mounted as env vars| Pod2[order-service pod]
    
    RBAC[K8s RBAC] -->|controls who can\nread/write secrets| SEC
```

```yaml
# Secret (stored encrypted in etcd)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: db-credentials
type: Opaque
stringData:
  DB_PASSWORD: "super-secret-password"
  JWT_SECRET: "another-secret"

---
# Reference in pod — app sees it as env var
spec:
  containers:
  - name: api
    envFrom:
    - secretRef:
        name: db-credentials
    - configMapRef:
        name: app-config
```

> ✅ **Result:** Secrets centralized, encrypted, RBAC-controlled. Rotation in one place propagates everywhere.

