## 8. Problem 7: Multi-Region & Multi-AZ Complexity

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

Your users are in Mumbai, Singapore, and Frankfurt. You want low latency for all of them. On EC2 you must:
- Manually provision EC2s in 3 regions
- Set up cross-region load balancing (Route 53 latency routing)
- Sync deployments across 3 regions manually
- Handle AZ failures by manually adjusting ASG configs

A single `terraform apply` mistake can take down prod in one region while leaving stale versions running in others.

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Tools like **Argo CD** (GitOps) + **Kubernetes Federation** or multiple EKS clusters behind **AWS Global Accelerator** handle this elegantly.

```mermaid
graph TD
    GR[GitHub Repo\nSingle Source of Truth] -->|GitOps sync| AC[Argo CD]
    
    AC -->|Deploy v2.1| EKS1[EKS Cluster\nap-south-1 Mumbai]
    AC -->|Deploy v2.1| EKS2[EKS Cluster\nap-southeast-1 Singapore]
    AC -->|Deploy v2.1| EKS3[EKS Cluster\neu-central-1 Frankfurt]
    
    GA[AWS Global Accelerator\nor Cloudflare] -->|Latency routing| EKS1
    GA -->|Latency routing| EKS2
    GA -->|Latency routing| EKS3
    
    EKS1 -->|Pods in ap-south-1a & 1b| AZ1[Multi-AZ\nautomatically]
    EKS2 -->|Pods spread across AZs| AZ2[Multi-AZ\nautomatically]
```

With **Pod Topology Spread Constraints**, Kubernetes automatically distributes your pods across AZs:

```yaml
topologySpreadConstraints:
- maxSkew: 1
  topologyKey: topology.kubernetes.io/zone
  whenUnsatisfiable: DoNotSchedule
  labelSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: ecommerce-api
```

> ✅ **Result:** One Git push → consistent deployment across 3 regions. AZ spread is automatic.

