## 9. Problem 8: Observability is Hard

### 🔴 The Real-World Scenario

Production is slow. You SSH into one of your 12 EC2 instances. Check logs. Nothing obvious. The problem is on a different instance. You `grep` through 12 separate log files manually, trying to correlate events across services. By the time you find the slow query, it's been 2 hours.

### 🟢 How Kubernetes Fixes It

Kubernetes integrates seamlessly with the **cloud-native observability stack**: Prometheus + Grafana + Loki + Jaeger (or OpenTelemetry).

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph "Kubernetes Cluster"
        P1[Pod: api]
        P2[Pod: payment]
        P3[Pod: order]
    end

    P1 -->|metrics /metrics| PROM[Prometheus]
    P2 -->|metrics /metrics| PROM
    P3 -->|metrics /metrics| PROM
    
    P1 -->|structured logs| LOKI[Loki\nLog Aggregation]
    P2 -->|structured logs| LOKI
    P3 -->|structured logs| LOKI
    
    P1 -->|traces| JAEGER[Jaeger / Tempo\nDistributed Tracing]
    P2 -->|traces| JAEGER
    P3 -->|traces| JAEGER
    
    PROM --> GRAF[Grafana\nUnified Dashboard]
    LOKI --> GRAF
    JAEGER --> GRAF
    
    PROM -->|AlertManager| SLACK[Slack / PagerDuty]
```

```bash
# One command to see all logs from ALL pods of a service:
kubectl logs -l app=payment-service --all-namespaces --since=1h | grep ERROR

# Or with stern (multi-pod log tailing):
stern payment-service --since 1h
```

> ✅ **Result:** One dashboard. Correlate logs, metrics, and traces across all pods in seconds.

